Let $x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n$ be such numbers. By AM-GM, we have 
\begin{align*}
\frac{x_1 + x_2 + \cdots + x_n}{n} \geq \sqrt[n]{x_1x_2\cdots x_n}. 
\end{align*}
Thus
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000}{n} &\geq \sqrt[n]{x_1x_2\cdots x_n}, \\
(1000/n)^n &\geq x_1x_2\cdots x_n. 
\end{align*}
AH aa. Our hand can compute multi-variable AM-GM as $n$ gets large. 
If $n = 1000,$ we then have 
\begin{align*}
x_1x_2\cdots x_n &= 1000^{1000}, \\
x_1^4x_2^4\cdots x_n^4 &= 1000^{4000}. 
\end{align*}
Plugging this into HH's inequality, we find the upper bound of $S = x_1^4 + x_2^4 + \cdots + x_n^4$:
\[S \leq 1000 \cdot 1000^{4000} = 1000^{4001}.\]
Since $1000^{4001} > 512000,$ $n = 1000$ does not work.
Note that $x_i = 8$ and $x_j = 2$ will work. Thus, the smallest answer is $n = \boxed{125}.$</think>
